        <body>
            <pb n="1"/>
            <p rend="align(right)"><placeName>Philadelphia</placeName>
                <date>Sepr. 15<hi rend="sup">th</hi>. Tishry 11<hi rend="sup">th</hi>.
                5603</date>.</p>
            <p>Dear Uncle.</p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">Ever since your letter was recd. I have been quite busy<lb/> with
                various matters; and was at last afraid that I should not<lb/> remain the
                    <add>אתרוג</add>; but while I was out yesterday a box arrived from<lb/>
                <persName>Mr. Kursheedt</persName>, and among other things it contained two for
                you,<lb/> which I sent off per this afternoon's boat directed to you, care of<lb/>
                <persName>J. I Cohen <sic>jr</sic></persName> who will no doubt hand them over to
                you. <persName>Mr. K</persName>
                <sic>apologises</sic><lb/> for their bad looks, owing as he says to a long voyage
                which the<lb/> vessel had, which caused them nearly to rot. However sent as
                they<lb/> are we must be satisfied with them. My friends have disappointed<lb/> me
                much; and probably a week after <add>יום טוב</add> they may get here.<lb/> The
                holiday passed over quite agreeably to every body; <persName>Mr.
                Peixotto</persName><lb/> read <add>מנחה</add> and <persName>Jacob
                    Phillips</persName>
                <add>זמירות</add> the two <add>הפטרות</add> were said by<lb/>
                <persName>Mr. Abraham Nathans</persName> &amp; <persName>Mr. Peixotto</persName>; so
                that I had <add>מוסף שחרית</add>,<lb/>
                <add>כל נדרי</add> and <add>נעילה</add> which was about enough. But as I always go
                on my<lb/> own way, I fatigued myself but little. My discourse I shall<lb/> send by
                some private opportunity, but when I cannot say, as<lb/> I now know of no one going
                who will stop long enough to see<lb/> you. Perhaps <persName>Rosa Marx</persName>
                may go on; this would be a good<lb/> chance.</p>
            <p rend="indent(1)"><persName>Mr. G. Pesos</persName> the younger son of the old lady,
                is here from <placeName>N.<lb/> York</placeName> quite ill; and but little hopes are
                entertained of his recovery.<lb/>
                <persName>Dr. Jackson</persName> attend him, and whatever care can do for him is
                done.<lb/> We had a funeral on the day before <add>יום כפור</add>; a young man of
                great<lb/> learning died on <date>Monday</date>, after but a few hours illness, and
                no Jew<lb/> knew any thing about his being sick till he was dead. He kept a<lb/>
                classical school, and his name was <persName>B. F. Phillips</persName>.</p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">Please to tell <persName>Mr. Judah</persName> that I spoke to
                    <persName>Mr. Peixotto</persName> about old<lb/>
                <placeName>Jamaica</placeName>; and he thinks that to get real good the price would
                be if I<lb/> recollect right perhaps three Dollars the gallon. I intend making
                inquiry</p>
            <pb n="2"/>
            <p>whether some good may not be got here. <persName>Miss Wolff</persName> is to married
                to <persName>Mr Lyons</persName><lb/> this day two weeks. <persName>Mrs
                    Cozens</persName> &amp; <persName>Mary Ann<add>?</add></persName> desire their
                love, and say<lb/> you must come on again in the spring, and try what
                    <placeName>Philadelphia</placeName><lb/> air will do for you. All your friends
                desire to be remembered in return,<lb/> I need not name them all.</p>
            <p rend="indent(1)"><persName>Mr. Kursheedt</persName> complains of not having been well
                lately; he<lb/> of course charges for the present parcel of Citrons, but says
                that<lb/> if new ones should arrive before <add>יום טוב</add> he will send some on
                to<lb/> me without charge.</p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">Wishing you much <add>שמחת יום טוב</add>, and desiring my best
                respects<lb/> to <persName>Aunt R.</persName>
                <persName>Mr. DJ.</persName>
                <persName>Rachel</persName> to the <persName>Blocks</persName>, as also to all
                friends</p>
            <p rend="indent(2)">I remain</p>
            <p rend="indent(3)">Your obt. nephew</p>
            <p rend="indent(4)">
                <persName role="author">Isaac Leeser</persName>
            </p>
            <pb n="4"/>
            <p>
                <addressee>Mr Zalma Rehine</addressee>
            </p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">
                <placeName>cor. of German &amp; Hammond<add>?</add></placeName>
            </p>
            <p rend="indent(2)">
                <placeName>Baltimore</placeName>
            </p>
            <p rend="indent(3)">
                <placeName>Md</placeName>
            </p>
